REPORT 2 — Legal‑to‑HIPAA Data Mapping Lab (Mock Incident)
Title: ePHI Exposure Risk in Legal Intake Workflow — Data Flow & HIPAA Safeguard Mapping
Region: North America
Industry: Legal + Healthcare Hybrid (Medical malpractice law firm)
Author: Ssambra — Identity Auditor & Threat Sentinel

1. Executive Summary
A medical malpractice law firm discovered that its client intake process was unintentionally collecting Electronic Protected Health Information (ePHI) through unsecured channels, including:

Unencrypted email attachments

A web form lacking TLS enforcement

Physical mail scanned on a workstation without access controls

This report documents the end‑to‑end data flow, identifies HIPAA safeguard violations, and demonstrates your ability to map legal workflows to healthcare compliance requirements.

2. Background
The law firm handles sensitive medical records as part of litigation. Although not a covered entity, the firm acts as a Business Associate under HIPAA when handling ePHI.

A paralegal raised concerns after noticing clients frequently submitted medical records through the general intake email address.

Your role:

Map the data flow

Identify ingress points

Apply HIPAA citations

Recommend safeguards

3. Scope
This assessment covers:

Intake → Processing → Storage → External Sharing

Administrative, Physical, and Technical HIPAA safeguards

Human behavior risks in legal workflows

4. Data Flow Summary
Ingress Points Identified
Email Intake (intake@lawfirm.com)

Clients attach medical records without encryption

No automatic forwarding rules documented

Web Intake Form

TLS not enforced (HTTP fallback allowed)

No consent banner explaining data handling

Physical Mail → Scanning Station

Shared workstation

No unique user authentication

Scans stored temporarily on local drive

Phone Intake Notes

Staff manually type medical details into CRM

No audit trail

5. HIPAA Safeguard Mapping
Finding 1 — Unsecured Email Intake
HIPAA Citation:

§164.312(e)(1) — Transmission Security

§164.308(a)(1) — Security Management Process

Issue:  
Clients routinely send medical records via unencrypted email.

Risk:  
Interception, unauthorized disclosure.

Finding 2 — Web Form Without TLS Enforcement
HIPAA Citation:

§164.312(c)(1) — Integrity Controls

§164.312(a)(1) — Access Control

Issue:  
Form allows HTTP fallback, exposing data in transit.

Risk:  
Man‑in‑the‑middle attacks.

Finding 3 — Shared Scanning Workstation
HIPAA Citation:

§164.310(b) — Workstation Use

§164.312(a)(1) — Unique User Identification

Issue:  
Multiple staff use the same login; no audit trail.

Risk:  
No accountability for ePHI handling.

Finding 4 — Manual CRM Entry Without Audit Logs
HIPAA Citation:

§164.312(b) — Audit Controls

Issue:  
No record of who entered or modified client medical details.

Risk:  
Data integrity cannot be verified.

6. Human Behavior Analysis (Psychology Lens)
Cognitive Bias: “Administrative Convenience”
Staff default to the easiest method (email) even when insecure.

Normalization of Deviance
Over time, risky shortcuts become “normal” because no incidents have occurred.

Authority Gradient
Paralegals hesitate to challenge attorneys about insecure practices.

7. Recommendations
Immediate Controls
Enforce TLS on all web forms

Enable email encryption for attachments

Require unique logins on scanning workstation

Governance Controls
Create a HIPAA‑aligned Data Handling Policy

Train staff on Business Associate obligations

Implement quarterly audits of intake workflows

Technical Controls
Auto‑encrypt inbound attachments

Move scanning workflow to a secure cloud folder

Enable CRM audit logging

